@startuml recall-consolidate-watermark
' The key "snap" picture: an LSN number line with consolidated_lsn (the
' watermark) as the divider between the Consolidate tier (lsn <= W) and the
' Recall tier (lsn > W). BEFORE a consolidation Recall owns (W, N]; AFTER,
' consolidation snaps (W, N] into a new shard and the watermark advances
' W -> N. The grace-bounded trim reclaims Recall only up to the 2nd-newest
' shard's watermark, so the rows in (grace_W, N] stay in Recall one extra
' generation as a safety buffer for in-flight queries on the older shard.

title The seam "snaps": consolidated_lsn advances W -> N, grace-bounded trim

skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Helvetica
skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam NoteFontSize 11
skinparam rectangleBorderThickness 1

' ===================== BEFORE =====================
rectangle "BEFORE consolidation" as before #FDF3E7 {

  rectangle "Consolidate tier (shards on S3)\nOWNS  lsn <= W\n[shard gen-2 wm=Wg]  [shard gen-1 (newest) wm=W]" as cBefore #E7F3FD
  rectangle "Recall tier (pgvector)\nOWNS  lsn > W\nrows in (W, N]  <- queryable now" as rBefore #E9F7E9

  note bottom of cBefore
    LSN number line:
    0 ......... Wg ......... W |  W+1 ......... N
    [====== Consolidate =====]  [==== Recall ====]
                              ^
                       consolidated_lsn = W
                          (the watermark)
  end note

  cBefore -[hidden]right-> rBefore
}

' the "snap" transition
note as snap #LightYellow
  ====  CONSOLIDATION  ====
  1. snapshot Recall up to max(lsn) = N
  2. build a NEW shard from (W, N]
  3. COMMIT consolidated_lsn = N    (commit the shard FIRST)
  4. grace-bounded TRIM              (only AFTER commit)
  The watermark SNAPS:  W  -->  N
end note

before -down[hidden]-> snap

' ===================== AFTER =====================
rectangle "AFTER consolidation" as after #FDF3E7 {

  rectangle "Consolidate tier (shards on S3)\nOWNS  lsn <= N\n[gen-2 wm=W]  [gen-1 (newest) wm=N]  <- the snapped (W,N] lives here now" as cAfter #E7F3FD
  rectangle "Recall tier (pgvector)\nOWNS  lsn > N\nrows in (N, N']  <- writes that arrived after the snapshot" as rAfter #E9F7E9

  note bottom of cAfter
    LSN number line after the snap:
    0 ....... W |  W+1 ..... N |  N+1 ..... N'
    [===== Consolidate ======]  [== Recall ==]
                              ^
                  consolidated_lsn = N (advanced)

    GRACE BUFFER: trim hard-deletes only
    lsn <= 2nd-newest shard's wm = W, NOT N
    (keep (W, N] one extra generation).
    So rows in (W, N] STAY in Recall too:
      (W, N]  excluded from the union by the new
               shard (lsn > N is false), so NO duplicate,
               but still present for an in-flight
               query that resolved the OLD shard (wm=W).
  end note

  cAfter -[hidden]right-> rAfter
}

snap -down[hidden]-> after

note right of after #E9F7E9
  Why the grace buffer is safe:
  a query that resolved the OLD shard (wm=W) -- using the
  watermark of the shard it actually read -- filters
  Recall with lsn > W and finds (W, N] still there,
  so no rows vanish mid-flight. Once that shard is
  >= 2 generations old, the next trim reclaims (W, N].
end note

@enduml
